owen   2, from Gaelic <b>Ó Buadhacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Buadhachán</i>’."]},{"name":"Bowens","meanings":["Welsh, Irish (Mayo), and English: variant of   Bowen  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Americanized form of Dutch   Bouwens  ."]},{"name":"Owen","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Owain</i>, from Latin <i>Eugenius</i> (see   Eugene  ). This Welsh personal name is cognate with Old Irish <i>Eogán</i>, see 2 and 3.","Scottish and Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Eoghain</b> ‘son of <i>Eoghan</i>’. See   McEwen  .","Irish: from <b>Ó hEoghain</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Eoghan</i>’. See   Ewen  ."]}]},{"name":"Josiah","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Meaning ‘God heals’ in Hebrew; it is borne by a king of Judah, whose story is recounted in 2 Kings 22–23. This was fairly frequently used as a given name in the English-speaking world, especially among Dissenters, from the 18th to the late 19th century. Following several decades of disuse, this name has become increasingly fashionable since the 1970s, especially in the U.S. The spelling  <b>Josias</b>  was also in use among Puritans from the 16th century. The most famous English bearer is the potter  Josiah Wedgwood  (  1730–95 ). In North America this was a recurrent name in the Quincy family of Massachusetts; the best-known  Josiah Quincy  (  1744–75 ) was a pre-Revolutionary patriot, who died while returning from arguing the cause of the American colonists in London."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Josiah Bowen was born about 1670, in Wethersfield, Hartford, Connecticut, United States as the son of Benjamin Bowen and Sarah Cox. He married Susanna Clark on 9 November 1694, in Wethersfield, Hartford, Connecticut, United States. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died from October 1703 to November 1703, in At Sea."},"et":{"about 1670–October 1703 or November 1703":"umb